meta Subj1:"Physics"/Chap1:"Vectors & Equilibrium"/Topi1:"Basic Concepts"/Type1:K/Diff1:E/Stem1:"definition"/

q {
Q:"Which of the following lists of physical quantities consists only of vectors:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Time, temperature, velocity", b) "Force, volume, momentum", c) "Velocity, acceleration, mass", d) "Force, acceleration, velocity"
R:"Force, acceleration, and velocity all have both magnitude and direction, making them vectors. Time, temperature, mass, and volume are scalars."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(\\vec{a} \\times \\vec{b}\\) points along negative z-axis, then the vectors \\(\\vec{a}\\) and \\(\\vec{b}\\) must lie in:"
A:"c"
O:a) "zx-plane", b) "yx-plane", c) "xy-plane", d) "None of the above"
R:"The cross product of two vectors in the xy-plane is perpendicular to that plane, i.e., along the z-axis. By the right-hand rule, appropriate orientations yield the negative z-direction."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\hat{k} \\times \\hat{i} = \\)"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(\\hat{j}\\)", b) "\\(-\\hat{j}\\)", c) "\\(\\hat{k}\\)", d) "\\(-\\hat{k}\\)"
R:"Using the cyclic rule for unit vectors: \\(\\hat{i} \\times \\hat{j} = \\hat{k}\\), \\(\\hat{j} \\times \\hat{k} = \\hat{i}\\), and \\(\\hat{k} \\times \\hat{i} = \\hat{j}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"What must be changing when a body is accelerating uniformly along a straight path?"
A:"b"
O:a) "The force acting on the body", b) "The velocity of the body", c) "The mass of the body", d) "The speed of the body"
R:"Acceleration is the rate of change of velocity. Uniform acceleration means velocity changes at a constant rate. Speed may change, but velocity (a vector) definitely changes."
}

q {
Q:"The horizontal range of a projectile is maximum when it is thrown at what angle with a certain velocity?"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(30^\\circ\\)", b) "\\(45^\\circ\\)", c) "\\(60^\\circ\\)", d) "\\(90^\\circ\\)"
R:"Range \\(R = \\frac{v^2 \\sin 2\\theta}{g}\\). This is maximized when \\(\\sin 2\\theta = 1\\), which occurs at \\(2\\theta = 90^\\circ \\Rightarrow \\theta = 45^\\circ\\)."
}

q {
Q:"A paratrooper jumping out of an airplane is an example of:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Equilibrium", b) "Static Equilibrium", c) "Dynamic Equilibrium", d) "None"
R:"Initially, the paratrooper accelerates due to gravity. Once terminal velocity is reached (drag equals weight), net force is zero but motion continues, representing dynamic equilibrium. MCQ banks typically classify sustained motion under dynamic equilibrium."
}

q {
Q:"The torque on a body will be zero if the angle between \\(\\vec{r}\\) and \\(\\vec{F}\\) is zero or:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(90^\\circ\\)", b) "\\(180^\\circ\\)", c) "\\(270^\\circ\\)", d) "None"R:"Torque \\(\\tau = rF \\sin\\theta\\). It is zero when \\(\\sin\\theta = 0\\), i.e., \\(\\theta = 0^\\circ\\) or \\(180^\\circ\\) (force parallel or anti-parallel to position vector)."
}

q {
Q:"If we go away from the surface of the earth, a distance equal to one third of the radius of the earth, the value of \\(g\\) will be multiplied by:"
A:"b"
O:a) "1/2", b) "9/16", c) "1/9", d) "16/9"
R:"Gravity at height \\(h\\): \\(g' = g \\left(\\frac{R}{R+h}\\right)^2\\). Here \\(h = R/3\\), so \\(g' = g \\left(\\frac{R}{4R/3}\\right)^2 = g \\left(\\frac{3}{4}\\right)^2 = \\frac{9}{16}g\\)."
}

q {
Q:"For certain values \\(F\\) and \\(d\\), work done is zero when the angle between the force and displacement is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(0^\\circ\\)", b) "\\(30^\\circ\\)", c) "\\(90^\\circ\\)", d) "\\(180^\\circ\\)"
R:"Work \\(W = Fd \\cos\\theta\\). When \\(\\theta = 90^\\circ\\), \\(\\cos 90^\\circ = 0\\), making work zero regardless of force or displacement magnitude."
}

q {
Q:"The force acting on a body in the gravitational field at any point is equal to its:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Gravitational mass", b) "Weight", c) "Acceleration", d) "Inertia"
R:"By definition, weight is the gravitational force acting on a mass: \\(W = mg\\)."
}

q {
Q:"What is kinetic energy of a body of mass 10 kg moving with velocity 1 m/s?"
A:"c"
O:a) "10 Joules", b) "20 Joules", c) "5 Joules", d) "2.5 Joules"
R:"\\(KE = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 = \\frac{1}{2}(10)(1)^2 = 5\\) J. (Note: The paper says \\(1 \\, \\text{m/s}^2\\) which is acceleration; assuming typo for velocity)."
}

q {
Q:"Simple harmonic motion is mathematically represented as:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(a \\propto -x\\)", b) "\\(a \\propto x\\)", c) "\\(v \\propto -x\\)", d) "\\(F \\propto -x\\)"
R:"SHM requires a restoring force proportional to displacement and directed towards equilibrium, leading to acceleration \\(a = -\\omega^2 x\\), hence \\(a \\propto -x\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The frequency of second pendulum is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "1 hertz", b) "2 hertz", c) "0.5 hertz", d) "None of the above"
R:"A second pendulum has a time period \\(T = 2\\) s. Frequency \\(f = 1/T = 0.5\\) Hz."
}

q {
Q:"A body with frequency \\(f\\) would complete one vibration in:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(f\\) seconds", b) "\\(1/f\\) seconds", c) "1 second", d) "\\(1/T\\) seconds"
R:"Time period \\(T\\) is the time for one vibration, and \\(T = 1/f\\)."}

q {
Q:"The rate of evaporation depends upon:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Nature of liquid", b) "The temperature of liquid and air", c) "The area of the exposed surface of the liquid", d) "All of the above"
R:"Evaporation rate is influenced by liquid properties (intermolecular forces), temperature (kinetic energy), and surface area (exposed molecules)."
}

q {
Q:"The saturated vapour pressure of a given liquid:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Increases with rise in temperature", b) "Decreases with rise in temperature", c) "May increase or decrease with rise in temperature", d) "Remains unchanged with rise in temperature"
R:"Higher temperature gives more molecules enough kinetic energy to escape into vapour phase, increasing saturated vapour pressure."
}

q {
Q:"Suppose the coefficient of linear expansion of copper is 0.000156 per degree C. What will be the coefficient of volume expansion of copper sphere per degree C?"
A:"c"
O:a) "Same as that of linear expansion", b) "Two times as that of linear expansion", c) "Three times as that of linear expansion", d) "One half as that of linear expansion"
R:"For isotropic solids, volume expansion coefficient \\(\\gamma \\approx 3\\alpha\\). Thus, \\(3 \\times 0.000156\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Length of metal rod is 100 cm and coefficient of linear expansion of metal is \\(0.00002 \\, \\text{K}^{-1}\\). By how many centimeters will it contract when cooled through \\(50^\\circ \\text{C}\\)?"
A:"b"
O:a) "1.001", b) "0.150", c) "0.001", d) "0.01"
R:"\\(\\Delta L = L \\alpha \\Delta T = 100 \\times 0.00002 \\times 50 = 0.1\\) cm. Closest option is B, likely a typo in the source options."
}

q {
Q:"The Coulomb force in a medium of relative permittivity \\(\\epsilon_r\\) is given by:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(F' = F/\\epsilon_r\\)", b) "\\(F' = F\\epsilon_r\\)", c) "\\(F' = \\epsilon_r F\\)", d) "\\(F' = F_0/\\epsilon_r\\epsilon_0\\)"
R:"The dielectric medium reduces the electric field and force by a factor of \\(\\epsilon_r\\). Thus \\(F' = F_{\\text{vacuum}} / \\epsilon_r\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Capacity of a capacitor depends upon:"
A:"d"
O:a) "The distance between the plates", b) "The nature of the dielectric between the plates", c) "The size of the plates", d) "All of the above"
R:"Capacitance \\(C = \\frac{\\epsilon A}{d}\\). It depends on plate area (size), separation distance, and permittivity (dielectric nature)."
}

q {
Q:"The magnetic force \\(F_m\\) acting on charge \\(q\\) when it moves with a velocity \\(\\vec{v}\\) through a magnetic field \\(\\vec{B}\\) is given by:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(F_m = q \\vec{v} \\times \\vec{B}\\)", b) "\\(F_m = q v^2 \\times B\\)", c) "\\(F_m = q v^3 \\times B\\)", d) "\\(F_m = q v^4 \\times B\\)"
R:"The Lorentz magnetic force law states \\(\\vec{F} = q(\\vec{v} \\times \\vec{B})\\)."
}
q {
Q:"A substance which behaves like a magnet in the presence of a strong magnetic field is called:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Magnets", b) "Ferro magnets", c) "Electromagnets", d) "None of the above"
R:"Ferromagnetic materials exhibit strong magnetization only when placed in an external magnetic field due to domain alignment."
}

q {
Q:"In a circuit, if a resistance of the conductor is increased then current in the circuit will:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Increase", b) "Decrease", c) "Remain the same", d) "First increase and then decrease"
R:"Ohm's law: \\(I = V/R\\). Current is inversely proportional to resistance for a constant voltage."
}

q {
Q:"The phenomenon that the resistance of a metal falls exactly to zero at a few degrees above absolute zero is called:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Conductivity", b) "Low conductivity", c) "Super-conductivity", d) "Low resistivity"
R:"Superconductivity is the complete disappearance of electrical resistance below a critical temperature."
}

q {
Q:"Why should a resistance be introduced in a circuit in series deliberately?"
A:"b"
O:a) "To increase current and decrease Voltage", b) "To decrease current and voltage", c) "To make current zero", d) "To make voltage zero"
R:"Series resistance increases total resistance, thereby reducing circuit current. It also causes a voltage drop across itself, reducing voltage for downstream components."
}

q {
Q:"In a house circuit, all electrical appliances are connected in parallel to each other between the line and neutral wires to get:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Same current and different voltage", b) "Same current and same potential difference", c) "Different current but same potential difference", d) "Different current and different potential difference"
R:"Parallel connection ensures each appliance receives the same mains voltage while drawing current according to its own resistance/power rating."
}

q {
Q:"Power dissipated in a circuit in the form of \\(V\\) and \\(R\\) can be determined as:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(P= VI\\)", b) "\\(P= V^2/R\\)", c) "\\(P= R/V^2\\)", d) "\\(P= V/I^2\\)"
R:"Using \\(P = VI\\) and \\(I = V/R\\), substitution gives \\(P = V(V/R) = V^2/R\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Lyman series lies in:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Visible region", b) "Ultra violet region", c) "Infra red region", d) "Far-infra red region"
R:"The Lyman series corresponds to transitions to the ground state (n=1) in hydrogen, which involve high energy photons in the ultraviolet range."
}
q {
Q:"According to Bohr’s theory of hydrogen atom, an electron can revolve around a proton indefinitely if its path is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "A spiral of increasing radius", b) "A circle of constantly decreasing radius", c) "A circle of an allowed radius", d) "An ellipse"
R:"Bohr postulated that electrons only orbit in specific quantized (allowed) radii where angular momentum is an integral multiple of \\(h/2\\pi\\), preventing energy radiation."
}

q {
Q:"According to Bohr’s theory of hydrogen atom, the radii \\(R_n\\) of stationary electron orbits is given by the equation:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(R_n = \\frac{3 n^2 k e}{m v}\\)", b) "\\(R_n = \\frac{n^2 h^2}{4 \\pi^2 m k e^2}\\)", c) "\\(R_n = \\frac{n^2 e}{m v^2}\\)", d) "\\(R_n = \\frac{n^2 h e}{m v}\\)"
R:"Bohr radius formula derived from quantized angular momentum and Coulomb force balance is \\(R_n = \\frac{n^2 h^2}{4 \\pi^2 m k Z e^2}\\). Option B matches the structure."
}

q {
Q:"An interesting application of laser is the production of three dimensional images called:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Polygons", b) "Holograms", c) "Ovals", d) "None of the above"
R:"Holography uses laser coherence to record and reconstruct light fields, producing true 3D images."
}

q {
Q:"The laser device used to fragment gallstones and kidney stones is called:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Laser beam", b) "Laser scanner", c) "Laser lithotripter", d) "Ruby laser"
R:"Lithotripsy uses focused shockwaves or laser energy to break calculi into passable fragments."
}

q {
Q:"Production of x-rays is a reverse phenomenon of:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Photoelectric Effect", b) "Compton Effect", c) "Pair Production", d) "Annihilation of matter"
R:"Photoelectric effect converts photons to electron kinetic energy. X-ray production (Bremsstrahlung) converts electron kinetic energy into photons."
}

q {
Q:"The nucleus of hydrogen with symbol \\({}_1^3\\text{H}\\) is called:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Proton", b) "Deuteron", c) "Triton", d) "All of the above"
R:"\\({}_1^1\\text{H}\\) is protium, \\({}_1^2\\text{H}\\) is deuterium, and \\({}_1^3\\text{H}\\) (tritium nucleus) is triton."
}

q {
Q:"Elements with atomic number Z > 82 are:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Stable", b) "Unstable", c) "Small", d) "None"
R:"All elements heavier than lead (Z=82) are radioactive and undergo spontaneous decay."
}

q {Q:"Which of the following particles has very low penetration power?"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(\\alpha\\)-particle", b) "\\(\\beta\\)-particle", c) "\\(\\gamma\\)-particle", d) "All of the above"
R:"Alpha particles are heavy and doubly charged, causing rapid ionization and losing energy quickly, thus having very low penetration (stopped by paper)."
}

q {
Q:"Which of the following particles move with velocity of light?"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(\\alpha\\)-particle", b) "\\(\\beta\\)-particle", c) "\\(\\gamma\\)-particle", d) "All of the above"
R:"Gamma rays are high-energy photons and travel at the speed of light \\(c\\) in vacuum."
}

q {
Q:"A carbon nucleus emits a particle x and changes into nitrogen according to the equation \\({}_6^{14}\\text{C} \\to {}_7^{14}\\text{N} + x\\). What is x?"
A:"a"
O:a) "An electron", b) "A proton", c) "An \\(\\alpha\\)-particle", d) "A neutron"
R:"Beta decay increases atomic number by 1 while mass remains same. The emitted particle is an electron (\\(\\beta^-\\))."
}

q {
Q:"During Pair-Production which particles are produced?"
A:"c"
O:a) "Proton & Electron", b) "Electron & Neutron", c) "Electron & Positron", d) "Proton & Neutron"
R:"Pair production converts a high-energy photon into an electron and its antiparticle, the positron, near a nucleus."
}

q {
Q:"The Solid-State Detector is basically:"
A:"b"
O:a) "A forward biased PN-junction", b) "A reversed biased PN-junction", c) "A forward biased transistor", d) "A Photocell"
R:"Solid-state radiation detectors operate in reverse bias to widen the depletion region, allowing ionizing radiation to generate measurable current pulses."
}

meta Subj1:"Mathematics"/Chap1:"Number Systems & Sets"/Topi1:"Definitions & Properties"/Type1:K/Diff1:E/Stem1:"conceptual"/

q {
Q:"35 is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "A prime number", b) "An integer", c) "A whole number", d) "An irrational number"
R:"35 is a positive whole number and belongs to the set of integers. It is not prime (divisible by 5 and 7) and is rational."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\forall a, b \\in \\mathbb{R}\\), \\(a \\cdot b = b \\cdot a\\) is called:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Closure law of addition", b) "Associative law of addition", c) "Commutative law of multiplication", d) "Associative law of multiplication"
R:"The commutative law states that the order of operands does not affect the result of the operation."
}
q {
Q:"In \\(\\mathbb{R}\\), the multiplicative identity is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "-1", d) "None"
R:"Multiplying any real number by 1 leaves it unchanged, satisfying the identity property."
}

q {
Q:"The additive inverse of \\(\\frac{2}{3}\\) is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{3}{2}\\)", b) "\\(-\\frac{2}{3}\\)", c) "\\(-\\frac{3}{2}\\)", d) "0"
R:"The additive inverse of \\(x\\) is \\(-x\\), because \\(x + (-x) = 0\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The multiplicative inverse of 0 is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "1", b) "-1", c) "0", d) "Does not exist"
R:"No number multiplied by 0 yields 1. Division by zero is undefined."
}

q {
Q:"The value of \\(i^7\\) is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "1", b) "-1", c) "\\(i\\)", d) "\\(-i\\)"
R:"\\(i^7 = i^{4+3} = i^4 \\cdot i^3 = 1 \\cdot (-i) = -i\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(z = 2 + 3i\\), then \\(z^{-1}\\) is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{2}{13} + \\frac{3}{13}i\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{2}{13} - \\frac{3}{13}i\\)", c) "\\(-\\frac{2}{13} + \\frac{3}{13}i\\)", d) "\\(\\frac{2}{13} - \\frac{3}{13}i\\)"
R:"\\(z^{-1} = \\frac{\\bar{z}}{|z|^2} = \\frac{2-3i}{2^2+3^2} = \\frac{2-3i}{13} = \\frac{2}{13} - \\frac{3}{13}i\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The modulus of 3 is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "0", b) "9", c) "-3", d) "3"
R:"The modulus (absolute value) of a real number is its non-negative value. \\(|3| = 3\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The multiplicative inverse of \\(1 - 2i\\) is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{1}{5} + \\frac{2}{5}i\\)", b) "\\(-\\frac{1}{5} + \\frac{2}{5}i\\)", c) "\\(\\frac{1}{5} - \\frac{2}{5}i\\)", d) "\\(-\\frac{1}{5} - \\frac{2}{5}i\\)"
R:"\\(\\frac{1}{1-2i} \\times \\frac{1+2i}{1+2i} = \\frac{1+2i}{1+4} = \\frac{1}{5} + \\frac{2}{5}i\\)."
}

q {Q:"The set of integers is a subset of:"
A:"d"
O:a) "The set of natural numbers", b) "The set of whole numbers", c) "The set of prime numbers", d) "The set of rational numbers"
R:"Every integer can be written as a fraction with denominator 1, so \\(\\mathbb{Z} \\subset \\mathbb{Q}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\{1, 2, 3\\}\\) is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "An infinite set", b) "A finite set", c) "A singleton set", d) "Universal set"
R:"It contains a countable, specific number of elements (3), making it finite."
}

q {
Q:"The sets \\(\\{1, 2, 4\\}\\) and \\(\\{4, 6, 8, 10\\}\\) are:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Equal sets", b) "Equivalent sets", c) "Disjoint sets", d) "Overlapping sets"
R:"They share at least one common element (4), so they overlap."
}

q {
Q:"Write down the power set of \\(\\{9, 11\\}\\):"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\(\\{\\{9\\}, \\{11\\}\\}\\)", b) "\\(\\{\\emptyset, \\{9\\}, \\{11\\}\\}\\)", c) "\\(\\{\\{9\\}, \\{11\\}, \\{9,11\\}\\}\\)", d) "\\(\\{\\emptyset, \\{9\\}, \\{11\\}, \\{9,11\\}\\}\\)"
R:"A set with \\(n\\) elements has \\(2^n\\) subsets. For \\(n=2\\), subsets are: \\(\\emptyset, \\{9\\}, \\{11\\}, \\{9,11\\}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\Phi' =\\)"
A:"d"
O:a) "A", b) "\\(\\Phi\\)", c) "A'", d) "U"
R:"The complement of the empty set (containing no elements) is the universal set (containing all elements under consideration)."
}

q {
Q:"If p and q are two statements then their biconditional ‘p iff q’ is denoted by:"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\(p \\land q\\)", b) "\\(p \\lor q\\)", c) "\\(p \\to q\\)", d) "\\(p \\leftrightarrow q\\)"
R:"The biconditional operator \\(\\leftrightarrow\\) means both statements imply each other."
}

q {
Q:"The number of subsets of a set having three elements is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "4", b) "6", c) "8", d) "None of these"
R:"Number of subsets = \\(2^n = 2^3 = 8\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(A=\\{1,2,3\\}\\) and \\(B=\\{a,b\\}\\) then a function from A to B is:"A:"a"
O:a) "\\(\\{(1, a), (2, b), (3, a)\\}\\)", b) "\\(\\{(1, a), (2, B)\\}\\)", c) "\\(\\{(a, 1), (b, 2)\\}\\)", d) "\\(\\{(1, 1), (2, 2)\\}\\)"
R:"A function from A to B must map every element of A to exactly one element of B. Option a satisfies this."
}

q {
Q:"A matrix with a single row is called a:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Column matrix", b) "Row matrix", c) "Null matrix", d) "Identity matrix"
R:"By definition, a matrix with dimensions \\(1 \\times n\\) is a row matrix."
}

q {
Q:"A square matrix all of whose elements except the main diagonal are zeros is called a:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Null matrix", b) "Singular matrix", c) "Symmetric matrix", d) "Diagonal matrix"
R:"This is the definition of a diagonal matrix."
}

q {
Q:"A square matrix A for which \\(A^t = A\\) is called a:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Column matrix", b) "Symmetric matrix", c) "Skew-symmetric matrix", d) "Row matrix"
